{"id":"2010.04097","submitter":"Kevin Griffin","authors":"Kevin Patrick Griffin, Lin Fu","title":"A new ODE-based turbulence wall model accounting for pressure gradient\n  and Reynolds number effects","comments":"17 pages, 12 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In wall-modeled large-eddy simulations (WMLES), the near-wall model plays a\nsignificant role in predicting the skin friction, although the majority of the\nboundary layer is resolved by the outer large-eddy simulation (LES) solver. In\nthis work, we aim at developing a new ordinary differential equation\n(ODE)-based wall model, which is as simple as the classical equilibrium model\nyet capable of capturing non-equilibrium effects and low Reynolds number\neffects. The proposed model reformulates the classical equilibrium model by\nintroducing a new non-dimensional mixing-length function. The new mixing-length\nfunction is parameterized in terms of the boundary layer shape factor instead\nof the commonly used pressure-gradient parameters. As a result, the newly\nintroduced mixing-length function exhibits great universality within the\nviscous sublayer, the buffer layer, and the log region (i.e., $0 < y <\n0.1\\delta$, where the wall model is typically deployed in a WMLES setup). The\nperformance of the new model is validated by predicting a wide range of\ncanonical flows with the friction Reynolds number between 200 and 5200, and the\nClauser pressure-gradient parameter between -0.3 and 4. Compared to the\nclassical equilibrium wall model, remarkable error reduction in terms of the\nskin friction prediction is obtained by the new model. Moreover, since the new\nmodel is ODE-based, it is straightforward to be deployed for predicting flows\nwith complex geometries and therefore promising for a wide range of\napplications.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 8 Oct 2020 16:25:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-10-09"}
